Figure 3. Cicero Constructs cis-Regulatory Models Genome-wide from Sci-ATAC-Seq Data (F) A summary of the Cicero co-accessibility links between the MYOG promoter and distal sites in the surrounding region. The height of connections indicates the magnitude of the Cicero co-accessibility score between the connected peaks. The top set of (red) links were constructed from cells in phase 1, while the bottom (in blue) were built from phase 2. See also Figures S3 and S4.

Figure 5. Co-accessible DNA Elements Linked by Cicero Are Epigenetically Co-modified (E) The Cicero map for the 755 kb region surrounding MYH3 along with called MYOD1 ChIP-seq peaks from (Cao et al., 2010). Sites opening in accessibility are colored by their opening pseudotime (see STAR Methods), sites not opening in accessibility are shown in gray. Inset: 60 kb region surrounding MYH3 along with MYOD1 ChIP-seq and H3K27ac ChIP-seq signal tracks from Cao et al. (2010) and the ENCODE Project Consortium (2012). Only protein-coding genes are shown.

fromhttps://doi.org/10.1016/j.molcel.2018.06.044

Application Scenarios

ATAC-seqcis-regulationUse single-cell ATAC-seq data to identify cis-regulation, providing clues for uncovering long-range regulatory mechanisms of target genes.

GEOATAC-seqDownload single-cell ATAC-seq data from GEO: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSM2970932GSM2970932mixHL60GM12878This example uses the smaller GSM2970932 data set, which includes a mix of two cells: HL60 and GM12878.

  • GSM2970932_sciATAC_GM12878_HL60_counts.txt.gzpeakreads
  • GSM2970932_sciATAC_GM12878_HL60_indextable.txt.gzindex

GEOThis is a common format, and many articles provide this format in GEO. Interested parties can refer to this article to mine relevant data for their own questions.

co-acessiblityEvaluating co-acquisition scores

ATACco-acessiblityfeatureUMAPt-SNEFigureYa27t-SNEBecause single-cell ATAC data is relatively sparse, it is generally necessary to group cells with similar features together for co-acquisition scores. Therefore, dimensionality reduction is usually performed first. UMAP is used for dimensionality reduction here, but any other dimensionality reduction algorithm, such as t-SNE, can also be used. See Figure Y a27 t-SNE.

input_cds <- make_atac_cds(cicero_data, binarize = TRUE)

set.seed(1234)
# peak0For each cell, calculate how many expressed genes (or open peaks) are above the threshold. The default is that the minimum expression is greater than 0.
# peakFor each gene (peak), calculate how many cells have an expression level;
# rowDatacolDataA row or column will be added to rowData or colData
input_cds <- detect_genes(input_cds) 

#size factorCalculate size factor
input_cds <- estimate_size_factors(input_cds) 

#normalizationsize factornormalization: First, normalize by size factor and depth. Then calculate the lower dimensional space as the input file for the next dimensionality reduction.

input_cds <- preprocess_cds(input_cds, method = "LSI") 

#Dimensionality reduction
input_cds <- reduce_dimension(input_cds, reduction_method = 'UMAP', 
                              preprocess_method = "LSI") 
plot_cells(input_cds)

mixco-accessibilityBecause this is a mixture of two cells, it is divided into two large groups. When analyzing your own data, you should consider whether to calculate co-accessibility for the two groups separately. Here, for ease of presentation, they are mixed together.

make_cicero_cdscell_data_set (CDS)After dimensionality reduction, you can use make_cicero_cds to construct the cell_data_set (CDS).

umap_coords <- reducedDims(input_cds)$UMAP 
cicero_cds <- make_cicero_cds(input_cds, reduced_coordinates = umap_coords) #CDS  Build CDS

data("human.hg19.genome")

ciceroGvizGvizwashu browserCicero uses the Gviz package. Similar to Gviz, its parameters are difficult to navigate, making it difficult to achieve the desired results. Therefore, the following demonstration will use the Washu browser, focusing on converting the input file format.

washu browserDemonstrated using the Washu browser

co-accessibilitywashu browserConvert the co-accessibility information to the format required by the Washu browser.

conns_selected <- filter(conns, coaccess >= 0.5 | coaccess <= -0.5)
peak1 <- conns_selected$Peak1 %>% str_split("_",simplify=T)
peak1_chr <- peak1[,1] %>% as.character()
peak1_start <- peak1[,2] %>% as.numeric()
peak1_end <- peak1[,3] %>% as.numeric()
peak2 <- conns_selected$Peak2 %>% str_split("_",simplify=T)
peak2_cor <- peak2[,1] %>% paste(peak2[,2],sep=":") %>% paste(peak2[,3],sep="-") %>% paste(conns_selected$coaccess*10,sep=",")
conns_washu <- data.frame(V1=peak1_chr,V2=peak1_start,V3=peak1_end,V4=peak2_cor,V5=seq_along(peak1_chr)*2,V6=".") %>% arrange(V1,V2,V3,V4)
write.table(conns_washu, "conns_washu.txt", sep="\t", row.names=F, col.names=F)
